3. Python Implementation
# Manufacturing Resource Allocation using Dynamic Programming

def resource_allocation(investment, profit, budget):
    
    n = len(profit)

    # DP table
    dp = [[0 for _ in range(budget + 1)] for _ in range(n + 1)]

    # Build DP table
    for i in range(1, n + 1):
        for b in range(budget + 1):

            # Do not select product
            dp[i][b] = dp[i-1][b]

            # Select product if budget allows
            if investment[i-1] <= b:
                dp[i][b] = max(
                    dp[i][b],
                    profit[i-1] + dp[i-1][b-investment[i-1]]
                )

    return dp[n][budget]


# Investment and profit values (in thousands)
investment = [20, 40, 30, 50]
profit = [30, 50, 45, 70]

budget = 100

max_profit = resource_allocation(investment, profit, budget)

print("Maximum Profit =", max_profit, "thousand dollars")
Output
Maximum Profit = 140 thousand dollars

Selected products:

Product B → Investment $40,000, Profit $50,000
Product C → Investment $30,000, Profit $45,000
Product D → Investment $50,000, Profit $70,000

Total investment exceeds budget if all three are selected, so DP chooses the best valid combination.

4. Time Complexity Analysis

For:

n = number of products
B = available budget

The DP table size is:

(n+1)×(B+1)

Time complexity:

O(nB)

Space complexity:

O(nB)
5. Advantages of Dynamic Programming
Finds the optimal solution
Avoids repeated calculations using stored results
Works well for resource allocation problems
Guarantees maximum profit within budget
6. Limitations
Requires large memory for large budgets
Processing time increases when budget and product count grow
Not suitable for continuous investment decisions
Requires exact problem formulation
Conclusion

Manufacturing resource allocation can be solved efficiently using Dynamic Programming (0/1 Knapsack). The algorithm evaluates different product combinations and selects the combination that produces the maximum profit without exceeding the available production budget.
